"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657276","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Government Equalities Office take part in the annual Civil Service People Survey within the Department for Education. The Department’s results for 2016 were published on GOV.UK on Tuesday 6 December.</p><p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent body and is responsible for its own staff management, including conducting surveys of its staff. I have therefore asked the Chief Executive of the Commission to write to the Hon. Member with the information requested and will place a copy of the letter in the Libraries of both Houses.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-12-15T16:55:23.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657276/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657276/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657276/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-12","Government Equalities Office and Equality and Human Rights Commission: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether there is an annual survey of staff in the (a) Government Equalities Office and (b) Equality and Human Rights Commission.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","57244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657277","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>Since 1998 the Department occupies the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20-year PFI, the Department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>The leases for the buildings in question are included within the provisions of this PFI arrangement and are therefore not held by DWP. Therefore we are unable to supply the information requested.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T16:10:22.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657277/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657277/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which companies or organisations (a) hold and (b) own the lease for each of the 16 jobcentres in Glasgow; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","57273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657278","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-20","<p>As at 18 December 2016 there are 1,302 Concentrix related Mandatory Reconsiderations outstanding.</p><p> </p><p>The oldest case still outstanding was received on 28 November 2016, all other outstanding Mandatory Reconsiderations were received after 28 November.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-12-20T10:47:13.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657278/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657278/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657278/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-12","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 14 November 2016, HCWS251, update on HM Revenue and Customs' contract with Concentrix, of those Mandatory Considerations against Concentrix tax credit decisions that are still outstanding, what the dates were on which the cases relating to those decisions were first lodged; and what the date was when the case longest awaiting consideration was lodged.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","57162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657279","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>Current estimates suggest that 10,000 people will be affected by the policy in total. The Department does not hold information which estimates how many of those have a mental health issue. Nonetheless, the Department has worked in collaboration with a range of stakeholders to make sure the policy includes the right exemptions to protect the most vulnerable people; including those who have a mental health issue.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-15T15:37:25.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657279/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657279/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657279/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an estimate of the number of people aged under 21 who will be affected by the planned removal of the housing benefit element of universal credit who have a mental health issue.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","57250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657280","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>The available information on Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions in Great Britain is published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Information for Northern Ireland is the responsibility of the Department for Social Development. Northern Ireland statistics can be found at: <a href="http://www.dsdni.gov.uk/index/stats_and_research/benefit_publications.htm" target="_blank">http://www.dsdni.gov.uk/index/stats_and_research/benefit_publications.htm</a></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-20T11:31:17.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657280/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657280/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657280/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have been sanctioned by his Department in (a) Wansbeck constituency, (b) the North East of England and (c) the UK in the last (i) six months and (ii) three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","57281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657281","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>Current estimates suggest that 10,000 people will be affected by the policy. The Department has worked in collaboration with key stakeholders such as Crisis and Shelter to make sure the policy includes the right exemptions to protect the most vulnerable people, including those at risk of homelessness; we are therefore confident about the robustness of the policy.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-15T16:19:48.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657281/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657281/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657281/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the (a) number of people aged under 21 who will be affected by and (b) effect on the level homelessness of the planned removal of the housing benefit element of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","57290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657282","Department for Education","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Government is currently reviewing Section 36 of the Equality Act with a view to assessing its implementation given its costs and regulatory impact.</p><p> </p><p>Although requests for reasonable adjustments to common parts are in the first instance matters between disabled tenants and their landlords, these have implications for the provision and funding of care for disabled people, since funding to support such changes is a charge on the Department of Health-administered Better Care Fund which supports local authority health and social care services.</p><p> </p><p>The review is therefore taking account of the impact on public and private landlords, any consequences for landlords’ willingness to let premises to disabled tenants, and the implications of additional calls on the Better Care Fund for the existing types of support which that Fund currently provides. My officials are working closely with those in both the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department of Health on these issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will announce the outcome of the review in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-12-20T17:21:00.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657282/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657282/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657282/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-12","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to bring into force the parts of section 36 and Schedule 4 of the Equality Act 2010 that would enable residents to secure disability related alterations to the physical features of the common parts of let residential premises or premises owned on a commonhold basis; what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on that issue; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","57146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657283","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>Since the start of Universal Credit the Real Time Information (RTI) system has been helping to ensure that we get Universal Credit claims right by providing us with accurate and timely details of earnings payments from Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs.</p><p> </p><p>The system is working well with over 99% of individual employment records now being reported in real time. We expect the number of working claimants with earnings reported via RTI to increase as Universal Credit continues to roll out and claimant numbers increase accordingly.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T15:58:19.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657283/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657283/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657283/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 1 December 2016 to Question 55249, by what date the Government anticipates that the Real Time Information function of universal credit will make it possible to track claimant earnings.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","57078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657284","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>This policy will not affect Housing Benefit claimants; rather it will affect new claims to Universal Credit Full Service from 1 April 2017. This policy will also be implemented alongside the Youth Obligation – a new and intensive package of labour market support for 18-21 year-olds looking to get back into work.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-20T15:35:11.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657284/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657284/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657284/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of future changes to housing benefit for claimants under 21 years of age on (a) claimants' labour mobility and (b) the wider economy.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","57084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657285","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>Our department has reported mean and median gender pay gap data since 2008 as part of the annual release of Civil Service Statistics by the Office for National Statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The latest gender pay gap data (published in October earlier this year) can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p><p> </p><p>In October 2015, the then Prime Minister announced that new gender pay gap reporting measures being introduced across the private and voluntary sector from April 2017 would be extended to also apply across the public sector. We are actively working to ensure the gender pay gap data we report in future fully mirrors these new requirements.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-20T11:15:05.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657285/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657285/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657285/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans his Department has to publish information on the gender pay gap among its employees.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657286","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>We do not capture data specifically on complaints about response times for answering Universal Credit helplines. The other information requested is not collated centrally and could only be supplied at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T16:14:07.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657286/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657286/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657286/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the monthly average response time was for calls to universal credit helplines in each year since the introduction of that credit; what the longest response time was in that period; how many such calls were recorded as abandoned; and how many complaints about response times for those helplines were made in that period.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","57177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657287","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>DWP is committed to creating an environment with parity of esteem for both mental and physical ill health; where mental health can be discussed honestly and openly without fear of discrimination.</p><p>The Department holds the status of Mindful Employer and is also a disability confident employer.</p><p>All staff and Line managers have access to comprehensive support via Occupational Health, Employee Assistance Provision, The department also has membership with organisations offering employees access to a wealth of practical advice and support on all aspects of disability, including mental health.</p><p>Mental health remains a top priority under the new departmental Health and Wellbeing Strategy, ‘Working Well Together’, fully endorsed by Debbie Alder, executive level Disability, Health and Wellbeing Champion.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-20T10:51:11.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657287/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657287/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657287/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what measures his Department has in place to support those of its staff who have mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Helen Whately","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","57139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657288","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>The available data on clearances of claims by type (i.e. awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) to Personal Independence Payment (PIP), by a range of breakdowns including whether they were new claimants or Disability Living Allowance to PIP reassessment claimants and to a range of geographical levels within Great Britain, is available from Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>. Information regarding Northern Ireland is a matter for the Northern Ireland Office.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-16T13:14:08.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657288/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657288/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657288/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many disability living allowance claimants in (a) Wansbeck constituency, (b) North East England and (c) the UK who have reapplied for personal independence payment have been unsuccessful in their applications.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","57186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657290","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not measure the number of people visiting its network of Jobcentres.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on the claimant count, which show the number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit claimants by geography, can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T16:24:57.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657290/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657290/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Jobcentres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have used the services of jobcentre offices in (a) the UK, (b) Greater London, (c) the London Borough of Newham and (d) East Ham constituency in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","57170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657291","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>Access to free NHS treatment by British citizens returning here after living in another EU country depends on whether they intend to live here permanently. Their access to public funds depends on the type of benefit claimed and, for most income-related benefits, whether they are habitually resident in this country or the Common Travel Area. The state pension is contribution-based and the amount payable depends on the individual’s National Insurance record. Those already in receipt of the state pension when they return would continue to receive this at the same rate.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T16:37:32.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657291/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657291/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether British citizens returning from a period living in another EU country are fully entitled immediately to receive (a) NHS treatment, (b) access to public funds and (c) a full state pension.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","57171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657292","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>All existing Employment and Support Allowance claimants in receipt of the work related activity group component on 3 April 2017 who are re-assessed thereafter and remain in the work related activity group will continue to receive the component.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-20T11:25:30.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657292/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657292/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, following changes to the weekly support for new work-related activity group (WRAG) claimants on employment support allowance effective from April 2017, whether any pre-April 2017 WRAG claimants will receive the lower weekly payment if they are re-assessed as still being in the WRAG following the end of their review period.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","57149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657293","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary of their highest to lowest paid employees.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics do, however, publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organisation. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-16T13:23:56.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657293/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657293/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657293/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the highest-paid and lowest-paid full-time employee in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657294","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organization. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-16T13:10:37.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657294/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657294/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the pay of full-time staff in the highest pay grade in his Department and average full-time pay in that Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657295","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the oral statement on the Corporate Governance Green Paper of 29 November 2016, Official Report, Column 1408.</p><p> </p><p>The Green Paper can be found as follows: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/573438/beis-16-56-corporate-governance-reform-green-paper-final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/573438/beis-16-56-corporate-governance-reform-green-paper-final.pdf</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-16T15:06:55.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657295/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657295/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans his Department has to include worker representation on its departmental board.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657296","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>Since 1998 the Department occupies the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20-year PFI, the Department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>The leases for the buildings in question are included within the provisions of this PFI arrangement and are therefore not held by DWP. Therefore we are unable to supply the information you have requested.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T16:04:53.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657296/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657296/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, who owns the (a) Langside, (b) Castlemilk and (c) Newlands Jobcentre Plus offices.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","57075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657297","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-16","<p>The Prime Minister is clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government. The Department for Work and Pensions is leading work across Government to bring forward a social justice green paper in the New Year which will identify and address the root causes of poverty, building upon the two statutory indicators set out in the Welfare Reform and Work Act 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Child Poverty Unit’s main function was to support Ministers in exercising their duties in relation to the income-related targets set out in the Child Poverty Act 2010 and the associated child poverty strategy. Following the repeal of those targets, responsibility for child poverty policy and analysis transferred to the Department for Work and Pensions. The Social Mobility Commission Secretariat continues to be based in the Department for Education and the Secretary of State for Education is the lead Minister for the Commission.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-16T10:32:38.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657297/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657297/answer","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657297/answer/previousversion/26796","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Child Poverty Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many full-time equivalent staff currently work in the Child Poverty Unit.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","57065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657298","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Department has not met with the PCS specifically on this issue. However, I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given by the Rt. Hon David Gauke on 07/12/2016 to <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-12-01/55878/" target="_blank">UIN 55878</a>.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-15T16:48:33.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657298/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657298/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 7 December 2016 to Question 55878, on social security benefits: children, whether his Department discussed that matter with the Public and Commercial Services trade union.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","56948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657299","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department has not met with Unison specifically on this issue. However, Ministers have met with officials and a wide range of stakeholders whilst developing the non-consensual sex exception. The Government has also run a public consultation on all the exceptions which closed 27 November 2016. The Government will publish the consultation response in due course.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-20T16:43:24.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657299/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657299/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 7 December 2016 to Question 55878, on social security benefits: children, whether his Department discussed that matter with Unison.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","56937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657300","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Royal Society is currently examining the implications of Machine Learning, alongside the Royal Society and British Academy work on Data Governance. These projects aim to develop recommendations for data governance arrangements, including ensuring the UK remains a world leader in the use and governance of artificial intelligence. The project will involve experts from across disciplines, and will look at current and historical case studies of data governance, and of broader technology governance, from a range of countries and sectors. Initial recommendations are expected in 2017.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-19T10:44:26.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657300/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657300/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657300/answer/previousversion/26750","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Artificial Intelligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an assessment of the extent to which the recommendations of the report by the Executive Office of the President's National Science and Technology Council Committee on Technology, entitled Preparing for the future of artificial intelligence, published in October 2016, apply to the UK.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","56940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657301","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary of their highest to lowest paid employees.</p><p>The Office for National Statistics do, however, publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organization. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T15:25:04.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657301/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657301/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the highest-paid and lowest-paid full-time employee in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","56979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657302","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the oral statement on the Corporate Governance Green Paper of 29 November 2016, Official Report, Column 1408.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T15:53:55.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657302/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657302/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to include worker representation on its departmental board.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657303","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organization. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T15:25:56.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657303/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657303/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the pay of full-time staff in the highest pay grade in his Department and average full-time pay in that Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657304","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-15","<p>Her Majesty’s Government does not express a view on the level of exchange rates. The exchange rate is allowed to adjust flexibly in response to economic conditions and movements in sterling are determined by market forces.</p><p> </p><p>At the Autumn Statement, the Office for Budget Responsibility forecast that the depreciation of sterling between the beginning of June and the end of October will support exports and reduce imports in the short term, with net trade adding 0.3 percentage points to GDP growth in both 2017 and 2018.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-12-15T12:19:37.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657304/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657304/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-12","Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect changes in the value of sterling on export businesses since the referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","56972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657305","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Department has received a number of representations on the future of carbon capture and storage (CCS). This includes carefully considering the findings and recommendations made in the report ‘Lowest Cost Decarbonisation for the UK: the critical role of carbon capture and storage’, published in September 2016 by the Parliamentary Advisory Group on CCS, chaired by the noble Lord, Lord Oxburgh.</p><p>We are considering the options for CCS in the UK, and will set out our approach in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-15T16:06:49.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657305/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657305/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations he has received on the Government's decision to cancel the carbon capture and storage competition.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","57067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657306","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department launched a formal public consultation on 9 November on proposals to end electricity generation from unabated coal power stations by 2025 in Great Britain. Officials in the department are engaging a range of stakeholders as part of the consultation process. An assessment of stakeholders’ views will be published after the consultation ends in February 2017.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-19T11:43:41.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657306/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657306/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657306/answer/previousversion/26746","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent representations he has received on the potential removal of coal-powered electricity generation from the UK's energy mix.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","57068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657307","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-16","<p>Our current energy pipeline, published in the National Infrastructure Plan 2016 which includes investment to 2030, suggests that £18bn (or 9%) of total investment is to be publicly funded, £177bn is to be privately funded, whilst a final £12bn of energy investment will be jointly funded by the private and public sectors.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-16T10:42:44.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657307/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657307/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657307/answer/previousversion/26747","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Energy Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the public investment needed to maintain the UK's energy capacity in the next 20 years.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","57069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657308","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>We continue to work closely with all UK steel producers together with wider stakeholders, including with Trade Unions, fabricators and stockists, to explore actions industry and government can take to further support the UK steel sector. I have challenged the sector to produce a clear vision for UK steel in the context of our industrial strategy, as the best future for steel workers will be one based on sustainable long term investment by the steel companies.</p><p>The Department is fully assisting the sector with the development of its vision and we have commissioned research into future market opportunities for UK Steel and the capabilities it will need to capitalise on these. The research project is overseen by a joint project of my officials and sector representatives.</p><p>The Government has so far provided £126m to UK steel firms in compensation for energy costs. It has also taken action to prevent steel dumping within the EU. There are now over 40 trade defence instruments which will protect steel producers from unfair trade practices.</p><p>Furthermore on December 13, we published details of upcoming steel requirements for infrastructure projects, with data on government plans to use three million tonnes of steel to 2020. Together with our revised public procurement guidance, this will give the UK steel sector the confidence and certainty to invest for the future.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-12-19T16:22:33.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657308/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657308/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much he plans to financially invest in the steel industry in the UK in the next three years; and what plans he has to support steel workers.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","57189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657309","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The number of households classed as fuel poor in 2014 in (a) Wansbeck constituency, (b) North East England and (c) England can be found in the following table. We do not publish the number of households classed as fuel poor in the UK.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of households classed as fuel poor</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wansbeck constituency</p></td><td><p>4,259</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East England</p></td><td><p>139,490</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>2,379,357</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The fuel poverty sub-regional statistics can be found <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fuel-poverty-sub-regional-statistics" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-19T11:21:51.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657309/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657309/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many people are classified as fuel poor in (a) Wansbeck constituency, (b) North East England and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","57200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657310","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department is committed to ensuring the wellbeing and good mental health of its employees and has various ways in which this is done. The support includes intranet guidance material, trained Mental Health First Aiders, a staff Wellbeing and Mental Health group who offer peer-to-peer support and promote awareness of mental health issues more widely. Reasonable adjustments are also put in place where beneficial for individuals working arrangements. Additionally there is an Employee Assistance Programme for counselling support and the Occupational Health Service where individuals can be referred to by the Line Managers for assessment and recommendations to support the individual.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T15:26:36.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657310/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657310/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what measures his Department has in place to support those of its staff who have mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Helen Whately","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","57220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657311","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy collects data, including customers’ tariff information, from the energy companies as part of the domestic fuels inquiry This data is collected by region and not by constituency.</p><p>In the second quarter of 2016, 14 % of domestic standard electricity customers and 15% of domestic gas customers in the North East paid for their energy by pre-payment meter. By comparison 15% of domestic standard electricity customers and 14% of domestic gas customers in England and Wales combined paid for their energy by pre-payment meter. This data is published within our Quarterly Energy Prices publication and can be found in Tables 2.4.2 and 2.5.2 which is available here: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/quarterly-domestic-energy-price-statics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/quarterly-domestic-energy-price-statics</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-19T14:37:35.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657311/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657311/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many people are registered as using a pre-payment meter to access their electricity and other utilities in (a) Wansbeck constituency, (b) the North East and (c) nationally.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","57085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657312","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>The creation of the new department reflects the Government’s vision to put action on climate change and a low carbon economy at the centre of Britain’s economic future.</p><p>Action by my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State includes reaffirming the Government’s commitment to spend £730m of annual support on renewable electricity projects over this parliament; setting out details for the next Contracts for Difference auction where companies will compete for the first £290m worth of contracts for renewable electricity projects; proceeding with Hinkley Point C which will create 26,000 jobs; and consulting on how to close unabated coal-fired power stations.</p><p>At the Autumn Statement the Government announced £4.7 billion investment to enhance the UK’s position as a world leader in science and innovation, laying the foundation for delivering an ambitious Industrial Strategy and a low carbon economy.</p><p>Looking ahead to next year, following the setting of the Fifth Carbon Budget in July 2016, the department will publish the Government’s emissions reduction plan which will set out how we will reduce emissions through the 2020s.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-12-15T16:21:57.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657312/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657312/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he has taken to advance the green economy since his Department was established.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","57076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657313","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>Dame Julia Slingo informed the European Commission in October that she would be retiring from professional life and wished to stand down from the High Level Group. This was not unexpected, as Dame Julia has also stepped down as Chief Scientific Advisor to the UK Met Office as part of her retirement. The members of the High Level Group of Scientific Advisors are appointed by the Commissioner for Research, Science and Innovation in a personal capacity, based on a short-list recommended by an independent Identification Committee.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-19T14:35:06.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657313/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657313/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he had with Dame Julia Slingo in advance of her standing down from the Scientific Advice Mechanism High-Level Group of the European Commission; and what steps he has taken to replace her with another UK scientist.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","57113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657314","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>Following the Machinery of Government changes, the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is currently considering how best to align the reform agendas of its two predecessor Departments. This will include considering what the right footprint for the Department should be, in order to best deliver its objectives.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-15T17:11:24.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657314/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657314/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether it is his Department's policy to increase the number of policy-making civil servants based outside London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","57184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657315","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Department commissioned a report from Atkins into the greenhouse gas implications of underground coal gasification to inform Government policy about its development in the UK; this report was peer reviewed by academics and industry representatives.</p><p>The report finds that emissions from underground coal gasification would be too high to be consistent with our commitment to a low-carbon future, and would not accord with our recent ratification of the Paris Agreement. For these reasons, we are not minded to support the development of this technology in the UK.</p><p>The Atkins report can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/underground-coal-gasification-evidence-statement-of-global-warming-potential" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/underground-coal-gasification-evidence-statement-of-global-warming-potential</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-15T16:08:16.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657315/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657315/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Coal Gasification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his Department's policy is on underground coal gasification.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","57181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657316","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The members of the High Level Group of Scientific Advisors are appointed by the Commissioner for Research, Science and Innovation in a personal capacity, based on a short-list recommended by an independent Identification Committee. This short-list also serves as a pool for replacement of members of the group during its first term of office.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-19T10:45:07.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657316/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657316/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657316/answer/previousversion/26744","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the European Commission on appointing a UK scientist to the Scientific Advice Mechanism High Level Group; and whether he plans to seek such an appointment before the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","57180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657317","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>The proportion of (a) the Senior Civil Service and (b) policy-making civil servants working for the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and based in London is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Senior Civil servants based in London</p></td><td><p>96%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civil servants based in London engaged in policy making</p></td><td><p>91%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-15T17:12:54.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657317/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657317/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of (a) the Senior Civil Service and (b) policy-making civil servants in his Department are based in London.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657318","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) was formed on 14<sup>th</sup> July from the merger of the former Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS) and the former Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC)</p><p> </p><p>Since 14<sup>th</sup> July, BEIS has appointed 20 apprentices, and has a further 15 due to start within the next few weeks.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T16:27:00.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657318/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657318/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many civil service apprentices have been appointed by his Department since it was created.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657319","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>We are engaging with the European Commission about our state aid pre-notification to move from compensation to exemption for the indirect cost of the Renewables Obligation (RO) and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs (FiT). We aim to introduce the exemption for Energy Intensive Industries (EIIs) from 1 April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to provide relief to those EIIs most affected by the rising cost of electricity and has paid over £360m in compensation since August 2013.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-19T16:13:41.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657319/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657319/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657319/answer/previousversion/26765","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to (a) expedite the Government's application to the European Commission to exempt energy-intensive industries from the indirect costs of the Renewables Obligation and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs and (b) ensure that legislation on that exemption is in place before financial year 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","57227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657320","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>Fuel pumps are required by law to be of an approved design based on national and international standards including requirements for accuracy. Each pump must be tested and verified before use. Local authority trading standards monitor the market place and can require any pump found to be inaccurate or not meeting the requirements to be taken out of use.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T14:36:36.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657320/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657320/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Fuels: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what (a) mechanisms and (b) monitoring systems are in place to ensure that fuel pumps at filling stations deliver the correct amount of fuel so that motorists are not defrauded whether accidently or deliberately.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","57252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657321","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>We aim to introduce an exemption for Energy Intensive Industries from the indirect costs of the Renewables Obligation and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs from 1 April 2017. It is not currently necessary to allocate contingency funding for the continuation of compensation beyond April 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-15T16:51:43.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657321/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657321/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to secure contingency funding for the continuation of compensation for the indirect costs of the Renewables Obligation and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs for (a) the steel industry and (b) other energy-intensive industries beyond April 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","57226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657322","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Government has taken a number of measures to promote the use of sustainable and efficient energy measures in residential buildings.</p><p>On 8 December we published a consultation on the Future of Heat in domestic buildings. This consultation seeks views on a range of options that can keep heating bills as low as possible, ensure the UK has a secure and resilient energy system and reduce carbon emissions cost-effectively at home. On 14<sup>th</sup> December, we also published the response to our consultation on reforms to the Renewable Heat Incentive. The reforms will focus on long-term decarbonisation, promote technologies with a credible role to play in that transition and offer better value for money for taxpayers.</p><p>The Government has already introduced a number of provisions to drive energy efficiency improvements in both domestic and non-domestic privately rented property through the Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property) (England and Wales) Regulations 2015. Landlords will be required by law to have improved the energy efficiency rating of the properties they let to an Energy Performance Certificate rating of at least an E from April 2018. <br> <br> The Energy Company Obligation (ECO), and its successor, will continue to deliver energy efficiency improvements out to 2022. <br> <br> We also commissioned an independent review into consumer advice, protection, standards and enforcement for home energy efficiency and renewable energy measures which will be published imminently.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-15T16:09:36.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657322/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657322/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to outline his Department's strategy for promoting the use of sustainable and efficient energy measures in residential homes.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","57241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657323","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>Companies House received the following number of complaints on breaches of the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009 by overseas companies.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Complaints</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010 (from 1 October)</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 (to date)</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>97</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Two of the complaints resulted in compliance by the company and one case resulted in prosecution. In the other cases it was found that there was insufficient evidence for prosecution action.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-15T17:14:24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657323/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657323/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Foreign Companies: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many complaints have been received on breaches of the Overseas Companies Regulations 2009 by overseas companies; and how many such complaints resulted in (a) compliance or (b) prosecution.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657324","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>There are currently 32 interns working in the Department. They are paid at the pay band minima for the grade they are recruited into, which is comparable to the pay received by permanent employees.</p><p> </p><p>The total duration of an internship must be less than 2 years.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-15T17:17:18.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657324/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657324/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many interns are currently working in his Department; at what rate those interns are paid; and what the maximum length of an internship is.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657325","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>Since 2007, Innovate UK has invested over £1.8 billion in innovation, with match funding from businesses nearly doubling this. The economic return from this investment is estimated to be up to £7.30 gross value added for every £1 invested. The increase in jobs is estimated at around 55,000 – or 7 jobs for every organisation supported.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to core investment by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, other government departments have policy objectives requiring technology-led innovation – from reducing transport emissions to improving agricultural productivity. Many of these programmes are run in partnership with Innovate UK.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-20T16:45:11.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657325/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657325/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Innovate UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of Innovate UK on (a) investment, (b) job creation and (c) the economy.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657326","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy are not currently operating any redundancy schemes.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-20T16:58:37.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657326/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657326/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what redundancy schemes his Department is currently operating.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657327","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>As of 13<sup>th</sup> December 2016, there are 11 individuals in the Redeployment pool of the former Department of Energy and Climate Change and 23 surplus staff in the former Department for Business Innovation and Skills. The former Department for Business Innovation and Skills does not operate a Redeployment pool.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-20T16:47:00.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657327/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657327/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Labour Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many civil servants in each unit of his Department are in the redeployment pool.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657328","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>Innovate UK’s core budget (Admin, Programme and Capital) from the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy over the last five financial years was:</p><p> </p><p>2011/12 - £370m</p><p>2012/13 - £439m</p><p>2013/14 - £451m</p><p>2014/15 - £426m</p><p>2015/16 - £547m</p><p> </p><p>Its budget for 2016/17 is £586m. At the 2015 Autumn Statement the Government committed to protecting, in cash terms, total spending on business led innovation through Innovate UK for the duration of the Parliament. In 2016 an additional £100m was committed for the Biomedical Catalyst and a further £2bn for R&amp;D by the end of the Parliament. Innovate UK’s annual budget is confirmed at the beginning of each Financial Year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-19T16:24:52.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657328/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657328/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Innovate UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what Innovate UK's budget (a) was in each of the last five financial years and (b) will be in each of the next four financial years.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657329","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>Workforce planning for the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service (Acas) is based on maintaining approximately the same number of staff as at present.</p><p> </p><p>As is the case for other public bodies, Acas has not yet had confirmation of financial allocations for future years. Acas may need to reflect any material changes to those allocations in its subsequent workforce planning.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-20T16:37:47.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657329/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657329/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","ACAS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has for the future staffing of the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57267"
