16:28:45.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657330/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657330/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what public appointments he has made in 2016.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657331","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>UK Shared Business Services Ltd (UKSBS) is a company owned by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and a number of the Department’s Arm’s Length Bodies. UKSBS provides a range of back office services to its owners and to other arm’s length bodies. The Department had previously decided that these services would be transferred to other public sector providers or the private sector and that the company would be closed. However some of the assumptions that underpinned that decision are no longer valid. Furthermore the demand for back office services has changed as a result of new proposals announced by the Government including, for example, the recent Machinery of Government changes and the creation of UK Research and Innovation (subject to Parliament). The Department is committed to modernisation, increasing flexibility and reducing operating costs, especially through the application of innovative technology and digital services. The Department is currently reviewing how its back office services should be provided in the future and the role that UKSBS might play in that provision. In the meantime UKSBS continues to provide services to its customers and will make an important contribution to the creation of, and transition to, UK Research and Innovation.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T16:30:21.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657331/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657331/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","UK Shared Business Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his plans are for the future of UK Shared Business Services Ltd; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657332","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Competition and Market Authority and Land Registry take part in the annual Civil Service People Survey. Ordnance Survey takes part in the Best Companies engagement survey.</p><p> </p><p>All three organisations make their results available through their respective websites.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T16:19:51.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657332/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657332/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what annual staff surveys are carried out at the (a) Competition and Markets Authority, (b) Land Registry and (c) Ordnance Survey; and if he will place the results of each of those surveys in the Library.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657333","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>The estimated cost for using external agencies for recruitment to Senior Civil Service posts in 2014/15 was:</p><p> </p><p>Department for Business, Innovation and Skills £155,000</p><p>Department for Energy and Climate Change £176,080</p><p> </p><p>Information for later years is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T16:32:16.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657333/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657333/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657333/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the cost of using external agencies for recruitment of senior civil service posts in (a) his Department, (b) the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and (c) the former Department for Energy and Climate Change in the last year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657334","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy operates from offices in Nottingham, Cambridge, Gateshead, Billingham, Manchester, Warrington, London, Aberdeen, Guildford, Bristol, Cardiff, Birmingham, Sheffield, Watford and Leeds.</p><p> </p><p>Following the Machinery of Government changes, BEIS is currently considering how best to align the reform agendas of its two predecessor Departments. This will include considering what the right footprint for the Department should be, in order to best deliver its objectives.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-20T16:32:12.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657334/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657334/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the location is of each office from which his Department operates; and which of those offices are planned for closure.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657335","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>Former Department for Energy and Climate Change (including non-Departmental Public Bodies (NDPBs)) spend on consultancy and temporary staff for 2014-15 and 2015-16 can be found in note 7 of the Remuneration and Staff Report section of the Annual Report and Accounts 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>Former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (including NDPBs) spend on non-permanent staff for 2015-16 can be found in the Staff numbers and related costs section (page 108) of the Annual Report and Accounts 2015-16.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T16:35:21.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657335/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657335/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much (a) his Department, (b) the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and (c) the former Department for Energy and Climate Change spent on non-payroll staff in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657336","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>At the end of October 2016, there were 186 non payroll staff working in the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>As at 31 March 2016 the number of non-payroll staff working in the former Department for (a) Business, Innovation and Skills and (b) Energy and Climate Change, is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Department</p></td><td><p>Number of non payroll staff</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Business, Innovation and Skills</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Energy and Climate Change</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-19T16:36:55.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657336/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657336/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many non-payroll staff are employed by his Department; and how many such staff were employed by the former Department for (a) Business, Innovation and Skills and (b) Energy and Climate Change in the last year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657337","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Government intends to provide further details about the Patient Capital Review announced by the Prime Minister on 21 November in the forthcoming Industrial Strategy Discussion Paper. The HM Treasury-led review will be supported by an advisory panel chaired by Sir Damon Buffini. The members of the advisory panel will not be remunerated. As such, no specific budget has been allocated by HM Treasury to the advisory panel.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-15T15:06:12.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657337/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657337/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-12","Patient Capital Advisory Panel","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 3.36 of the Autumn Statement 2016, what budget has been allocated to the advisory panel on Patient Capital; and whether members of that panel will receive a wage or expenses.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657338","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) administrative budgets to 2020 are subject to finalisation of Machinery of Government (MoG) transfers and the departmental transition, which will conclude by the end of the financial year. BEIS is committed to making savings in line with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Department for Energy and Climate Change Spending Review 2015 settlements. As part of MoG agreements, some of the Spending Review savings targets will be transferred to the Department for Education and Department for International Trade, in line with Cabinet Office MoG Guidance.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-20T16:43:06.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657338/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657338/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the planned efficiency savings from his Department's administrative budget are in each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657339","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-20","<p>As at 31 October 2016, 3211 staff were employed by the Department.</p><p>Workforce planning is continuing which will include staffing forecasts for future years.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-20T16:34:02.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657339/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657339/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many civil servants his Department employs; and how many such staff his Department plans to employ in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","57275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657340","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department for International Trade does not produce forecasts of exports.</p><p>The forecasts published by the Office for Budget Responsibility as part of the November 2016 Autumn Statement are given in Table 1 below.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Forecasts of UK Exports, £billion, current prices </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Exports, £ billion, current prices</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 (actual)</p></td><td><p>508.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 (forecast)</p></td><td><p>537.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 (forecast)</p></td><td><p>585.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018 (forecast)</p></td><td><p>614.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019 (forecast)</p></td><td><p>633.1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Source: Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR), November 2016 forecasts</strong></p><p><strong>Note: Since publication of these forecasts, the Office for National Statistics (ONS) has detected an error in the trade data which affects the actual export figure for 2015, and therefore the OBR forecasts for subsequent years. As a result of the ONS error, the 2015 figure for exports has been revised up to £513.1 billion. </strong></p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T13:09:58.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657340/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657340/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate his Department has made of the level of exports from the UK in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","57270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657341","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>As the UK leaves the EU, we have an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world, ensuring we become a global leader in free trade. We are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of countries and markets, in order to take all opportunities to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T13:35:54.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657341/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657341/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many bilateral trade deals he estimates the UK will sign by 2020.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","57236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657342","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-15","<p>Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets, in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade.</p><p> </p><p>We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-12-15T17:44:18.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657342/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657342/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Trade Agreements: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will make it his policy to prioritise a free trade agreement with (a) Israel and (b) the Palestinian Authority after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","57291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657344","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>The government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. In light of this, the government is considering all options including the design of future bilateral trade and investment agreements, and the most appropriate means of providing investors with the necessary protections.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T13:28:28.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657344/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657344/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of investor-state dispute settlement measures in supporting growth in international trade.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","57190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657345","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>As the Department for International Trade (DIT) is newly formed, we are currently scoping our medium to long-term resourcing plans. In the interim we are currently running an external recruitment campaign to meet our immediate resourcing needs.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T13:50:25.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657345/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657345/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many additional staff his Department plans to recruit in the next (a) year and (b) three years.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","57133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657346","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>I refer the hon Member for Nottingham East to the answer I gave to my hon Friend for Bristol North West on 31 October, UIN:50013.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T13:19:43.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657346/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657346/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","European Free Trade Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the potential costs and benefits for the UK of membership of the European Free Trade Association; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","57208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657347","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary of their highest to lowest paid employees. The Office for National Statistics (ONS) do, however, publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organisation. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p><p>As the Department for International Trade (DIT) is newly formed, we have not had the opportunity to contribute to the ONS publication. DIT’s statistics will be included in the next release, due for publication in March 2017.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","56992","2016-12-20T14:28:46.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657347/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657347/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Department for International Trade: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the pay of full-time staff in the highest pay grade in his Department and average full-time pay in that Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657348","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the oral statement on the Corporate Governance Green Paper of 29 November 2016, Official Report, Column 1408.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T13:58:35.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657348/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657348/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what plans his Department has to include worker representation on its departmental board.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657349","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-15","<p>All Trade Policy Group officials, except one, are based in London, as are the policy making officials in UK Export Finance. The rest of the department is primarily engaged in operational delivery.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-15T17:47:22.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657349/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657349/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what proportion of policy-making civil servants in his Department is based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657351","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary of their highest to lowest paid employees. The Office for National Statistics (ONS) do, however, publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organisation. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p><p>As the Department for International Trade (DIT) is newly formed, we have not had the opportunity to contribute to the ONS publication. DIT’s statistics will be included in the next release, due for publication in March 2017.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","57036","2016-12-20T14:28:46.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657351/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657351/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Department for International Trade: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the highest-paid and lowest-paid full-time employee in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","56992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657352","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-15","<p>The 2016 Autumn Statement announced additional resources, for the Department for International Trade (DIT), of up to £7m in 16/17, £21.6m in 17/18, £23.3m in 18/19 and £23.6m in 19/20 to strengthen trade policy capability.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-15T17:51:33.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657352/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657352/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657352/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what proportion of the £26 million, referred to in paragraph 3.34 of the Autumn Statement 2016, to recruit additional policy staff to support international trade issues will be allocated to his Department.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","56943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657353","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the oral statement on the Corporate Governance Green Paper of 29 November 2016, Official Report, Column 1408.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-20T12:34:36.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657353/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657353/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what plans his Department has to include worker representation on its departmental board.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657354","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Department now has over 300 staff with all posts being London based, plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels from the UK Permanent Representation to the EU.</p><p>DExEU Ministers have visited every region and nation of the UK, and we will continue to do so. We are travelling right across the country to ensure that all views are reflected in our analysis of the options, priorities and opportunities for the UK.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-15T15:25:48.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657354/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657354/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what proportion of policy making civil servants in his Department is based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","56959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657355","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary of their highest to lowest paid employees.<br><br>The Office for National Statistics do, however, publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organisation. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics. Due to the timing of the exercise the Department for Exiting the European Union was not included in this year’s figures but this information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:<br><br><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a> <br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","57031","2016-12-20T12:45:56.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657355/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657355/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the highest-paid and lowest-paid full-time employee in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","56987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657356","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>Government departments do not publish details of the salary of their highest to lowest paid employees.<br><br>The Office for National Statistics do, however, publish the salary ratio of highest to median earners for each Civil Service organisation. These ratios are published annually as part of Civil Service Statistics. Due to the timing of the exercise the Department for Exiting the European Union was not included in this year’s figures but this information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:<br><br><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a> <br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","56987","2016-12-20T12:45:56.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657356/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657356/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657356/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the percentage gap in earnings is between the pay of full-time staff in the highest pay grade in his Department and average full-time pay in that Department.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","57031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657358","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers given to Question 52878 on 17 November 2016, and Question 55997 on 12 December 2016.</p>The court case R (Miller) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union is ongoing and, as the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union said in his statement to the House on 7 November 2016, all those figures will be published in due course.","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","56975","2016-12-15T15:40:56.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657358/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657358/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657358/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the hourly rate is for employing additional non-governmental legal support for the court case R (Miller) v the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, relating to Article 50.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","56974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657359","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>We will set out our broad plans before triggering Article 50 by the end of next March, repeating the proviso as agreed by the House on 12 October 2016, without division, confirmed on the 7th December, that nothing we do or say should undermine the UK's negotiating position.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-20T14:51:16.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657359/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657359/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657359/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, in what format and by what date he plans to publish his Department's plan for the UK's negotiations on exiting the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","57211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657360","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>We want to see UK companies having the maximum freedom to trade with and operate in the Single Market, and for EU companies to be able to do the same here.</p><p>We are currently looking at all the options. To support this work, officials across Government are carrying out a programme of sectoral and regulatory analysis, which will identify the key factors for UK businesses and the labour force that will affect our negotiations with the EU. They are looking in detail at over 50 sectors as well as cross-cutting regulatory issues.</p><p>As the UK is party to the EEA agreement only in its capacity as an EU member state, once we leave the European Union the EEA agreement will automatically cease to apply to the UK.The model we are seeking is one unique to the United Kingdom and not an off the shelf solution.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-20T14:46:42.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657360/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657360/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657360/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","European Economic Area: Membership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of the UK remaining a member of the European Economic Area.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","57213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657361","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-15","<p>The relationship between the UK and our EU partners after we exit the EU will be the subject of negotiations that will start after we trigger Article 50, which my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has said will be no later than the end of March next year. This will include, amongst others, our future relationship with the EU on climate change.</p><p>UK policy on climate change has not changed following Brexit and the UK remains committed to international efforts to tackle climate change. Domestically, we are committed to delivering dependable, secure and low-carbon energy. Our Emissions Reduction Plan will set out how we will reduce emissions over the 2020s and will be produced in tandem with our Industrial Strategy. While we remain in the EU we will continue to engage constructively on new and existing EU legislation and regulation in this area.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-12-15T14:50:51.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657361/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657361/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657361/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what preparations his Department is making for the coordination with EU member states of efforts to tackle climate change after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","57172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657362","Home Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>The UK’s position on granting protection to those who need it will not change as a result of the referendum – we will continue to apply the Refugee Convention and provide protection for all those in need. The Government remains firmly committed to leading the way in working with the international community to tackle the global migration challenges. International engagement on migration – including cooperation with EU partners – will remain in our interest once we leave the EU.</p><p>We will provide sanctuary to those who need it but will continue to intervene at every point in the migrant journey to address the root causes of the global migration challenge. The Government has committed to resettling 20,000 Syrian refugees through our Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme over the course of this Parliament — that will not change as a result of the referendum and we are on track to deliver. A total of 4,414 people have been granted humanitarian protection under the scheme since it began. In addition to the scheme, the UK has pledged £2.3 billion in humanitarian aid to Syria and neighbouring countries.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-19T18:03:28.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657362/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657362/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what preparations her Department is making for the coordination of efforts with EU member states to support Syrian refugees after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","57173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657363","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to ensuring staff with mental health problems do not face any barriers to success. The Department has two dedicated disability champions and an equalities network to provide support. We are also in the process of introducing training for a number of our staff to enable them to become mental health first aiders. The Department is putting plans in place to ensure the steps established in the 2016 Talent Action Plan are in place in order to help the Civil Service become the most inclusive employer in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-20T14:18:49.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657363/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657363/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what measures his Department has in place to support those of its staff who have mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Helen Whately","Faversham and Mid Kent","Helen Whately","57141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657364","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-15","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers given to Question 52878 on 17 November 2016, and Question 55997 on 12 December 2016.</p>The court case R (Miller) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union is ongoing and, as the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union said in his statement to the House on 7 November 2016, all those figures will be published in due course.","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","56974","2016-12-15T15:40:56.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657364/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657364/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Department for Exiting the European Union: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 24 November 2016 to Question 53514, on Brexit, what the cost to the public purse has been to date of the (a) Government's appeal to the Supreme Court on triggering Article 50 and (b) the court case R (Miller) v the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, relating to Article 50.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","56975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657365","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Prime Minister has said we want a smooth and orderly exit from the EU, and to provide certainty where we can. How the government achieves that will depend on the nature of the negotiations and the agreement reached with the EU, but it would not be in the interests of either side– Britain or the EU – to see disruption. The government is considering all possible options, focusing on the mutual interests of the UK and the EU.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-20T14:41:00.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657365/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657365/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether it is his policy to negotiate a transitional agreement with the EU so that existing trading arrangements for UK companies will be able to continue beyond 1 April 2019; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","57205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657373","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-19","<p>When a company incorporates with Companies House, information is required about the company’s type, its name and registered office, its directors and shareholders, its share structure and, under measures that came into force in June this year, its beneficial owners – the people with significant influence and control over it. Copies of the company’s governing documents are also required.</p><p>A number of checks are undertaken to ensure this information is complete, formatted correctly and that it meets the requirements of the Companies Act 2006. If these requirements are not met, the application will be rejected and the company will not be incorporated.</p><p>Incorporation allows the company to take actions such as opening a bank account in its own name. But when it first seeks to do this, the company and the relevant officers of the company will be subject to due diligence processes by the bank or other relevant obliged entities with which it is entering into a business relationship. UK companies are subject to customer due diligence many times throughout their lifetime.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-19T14:57:04.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657373/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657373/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Companies: Registration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to improve the scrutiny of company formations, in the light of reports of UK-registered companies being used to operate international scams.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL4007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657374","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-28","<p>Since 10 October 2015, the Registrar of Companies has been required under section 1079B of the Companies Act 2006 to provide newly appointed company directors with information about their duties and responsibilities as a director. This information is contained in a leaflet which the Registrar sends to all newly appointed directors.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-28T13:20:36.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657374/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657374/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-12","Directors: Registration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to prevent people being registered as company directors without being aware of their responsibilities.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL4008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657375","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-28","<p>On 23 December the Ministry of Justice announced a consultation on ways to protect people from having their credit ratings affected despite being unaware of the claims made against them. The consultation, which will be launched in the spring will consider how the current system can be improved and reinforced to ensure that companies take all reasonable steps before they are able to apply to a court for a claim. We will also examine to what extent unscrupulous debt agencies have contributed to the problem.</p><p> </p><p>To accompany the consultation the Ministry of Justice will also launch a new public advice campaign on how to protect people unaware of their debts and will remind people of the important of informing companies of their new address.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4010 ; HL4011","2016-12-28T13:19:50.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657375/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657375/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-12","County Courts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to strengthen procedures designed to protect those against whom costs are awarded without their knowing that a case is proceeding in the County Court, resulting in a County Court Judgment being registered on their credit record.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL4009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657376","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-28","<p>On 23 December the Ministry of Justice announced a consultation on ways to protect people from having their credit ratings affected despite being unaware of the claims made against them. The consultation, which will be launched in the spring will consider how the current system can be improved and reinforced to ensure that companies take all reasonable steps before they are able to apply to a court for a claim. We will also examine to what extent unscrupulous debt agencies have contributed to the problem.</p><p> </p><p>To accompany the consultation the Ministry of Justice will also launch a new public advice campaign on how to protect people unaware of their debts and will remind people of the important of informing companies of their new address.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4009 ; HL4011","2016-12-28T13:19:50.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657376/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657376/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-12","County Courts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that companies which sue individuals for non-payment of monies in the county courts have taken adequate steps to ensure that they have the correct and up-to-date address for the person against whom they are taking action, in those cases where the individual does not lodge a defence.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL4010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657377","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-28","<p>On 23 December the Ministry of Justice announced a consultation on ways to protect people from having their credit ratings affected despite being unaware of the claims made against them. The consultation, which will be launched in the spring will consider how the current system can be improved and reinforced to ensure that companies take all reasonable steps before they are able to apply to a court for a claim. We will also examine to what extent unscrupulous debt agencies have contributed to the problem.</p><p> </p><p>To accompany the consultation the Ministry of Justice will also launch a new public advice campaign on how to protect people unaware of their debts and will remind people of the important of informing companies of their new address.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4009 ; HL4010","2016-12-28T13:19:50.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657377/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657377/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657377/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-12","County Courts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to penalise companies which repeatedly take action against individuals who do not lodge a defence and who are subsequently discovered not to have received any notification of the relevant County Court action.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL4011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657378","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-20","<p>Following a Call for Evidence last year we are exploring alternative methods to help employers in multi-employer schemes manage section 75 employer debts.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-12-20T15:59:43.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657378/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657378/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657378/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-12","Occupational Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they plan to take to prevent employers who participated in multi-employer schemes as partnerships, rather than through limited liability companies, from losing their homes and being made bankrupt as a result of section 75 debts relating to workers who were not in their employ.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL4012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657379","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>We are aware of reports of the raid on the Ahmadiyya office in Pakistan. The Government strongly condemns the persecution of all minorities, including the targeting of people based on their beliefs. Our concerns are reflected in the latest update to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual human rights report.</p><p>The Government regularly raises our concerns about the protection of minority communities, including religious minorities, with the Pakistani Government at a senior level. During his visit to Pakistan in November, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr. Johnson) raised religious tolerance and the importance of safeguarding the rights of all Pakistan's citizens. The Government continues to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to religious minorities, and to uphold the rule of law.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:35:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657379/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657379/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Pakistan: Ahmadiyya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Pakistan following reports of a raid on the Ahmadi community headquarters in Rabwah.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657380","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has advised that the Expert Panel has met on four occasions over the past four years. On each occasion a formal call for evidence was issued. With regard to the most recent report, the Panel received confidential correspondence on particular issues. Panel members were able to share private correspondence with the Secretariat that supports the Panel, where relevant. Where any evidence has influenced the reports it has been cited.</p><p>The HFEA has also advised that it approached John Zhang, following the publication of the abstract from the October 2016 American Society for Reproductive Medicine meeting, entitled “First live birth using human oocytes reconstituted by spindle nuclear transfer for mitochondrial DNA mutation causing Leigh syndrome”. A copy of the abstract is attached. The Panel also interviewed Prof. Zhang to further understand the methods used. The Panel’s report references the Zhang work.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL4015","2016-12-20T15:21:45.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657380/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657380/answer","Zhang abstract ASRM Oct 2016 (1).pdf","ZHANG ABSTRACT","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657380/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-12","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 17 October (HL2340) and 5 December (HL3452), whether any members of the expert panel convened by the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) shared private and confidential correspondence with members of the HFEA Executive that had not been submitted to the Authority as part of any formal calls for evidence; and if so, what were the particular circumstances that necessitated giving weight to any material not intended for publication.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657381","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has advised that the Expert Panel has met on four occasions over the past four years. On each occasion a formal call for evidence was issued. With regard to the most recent report, the Panel received confidential correspondence on particular issues. Panel members were able to share private correspondence with the Secretariat that supports the Panel, where relevant. Where any evidence has influenced the reports it has been cited.</p><p>The HFEA has also advised that it approached John Zhang, following the publication of the abstract from the October 2016 American Society for Reproductive Medicine meeting, entitled “First live birth using human oocytes reconstituted by spindle nuclear transfer for mitochondrial DNA mutation causing Leigh syndrome”. A copy of the abstract is attached. The Panel also interviewed Prof. Zhang to further understand the methods used. The Panel’s report references the Zhang work.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL4014","2016-12-20T15:21:45.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657381/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657381/answer","Zhang abstract ASRM Oct 2016 (1).pdf","ZHANG ABSTRACT","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657381/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-12","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 17 October (HL2340) and 5 December (HL3452), whether members of the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) expert panel approached John Zhang or were approached by him, and when any such contact was first made; and to what extent, if any, the recent recommendations of the HFEA expert panel were influenced by the John Zhang's unpublished data referred to in the journal <i>Nature</i> on 10 November.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657382","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998 ensures that workers who raise concerns of wrongdoing to their employer or a relevant external body (by making what is known as a ‘protected disclosure’) and suffer detriment as a result may seek redress through an Employment Tribunal.</p><p> </p><p>With regards to information on tax avoidance and evasion HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) gathers information from a number of sources including whistle-blowers. Any information which is provided to HMRC is treated as confidential and details of the individual providing the information will not be divulged, without consent, except where compelled by law.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not offer immunity from prosecution within the UK or in a third country where that country’s legislation is at odds with UK Legislation.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-12-21T12:36:09.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657382/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657382/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-12","EU Countries: Tax Avoidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the appeal in Luxembourg of Antoine Deltour against his conviction in June for theft, what steps they are taking to protect whistleblowers who expose companies’ aggressive tax avoidance schemes when those schemes are organised in conjunction with the governments of other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Lord Harries of Pentregarth",,"Lord Harries of Pentregarth","HL4016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657383","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>Whilst we have not raised this specific issue with the Israeli authorities, we call on all parties to appreciate the unique sensitivities in Jerusalem, a city which holds particular significance for many groups especially the three Abrahamic faiths of Christianity, Islam and Judaism.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:35:46.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657383/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657383/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Israel following reports of the confiscation of an Islamic cemetery adjacent to the Al-Aqsa mosque and the prevention of Palestinian burials from taking place there.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657384","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>​While we have not raised or made an assessment on this specific issue, we have consistently called on the Israeli government to ease movement and access restrictions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories, most recently on 5 December. We are also supporting the UN Access Coordination Unit to work with the Israeli Government, Palestinian Authority and aid agencies to facilitate the transfer of medical equipment and supplies, and patient referrals in and out of Gaza.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:36:17.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657384/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657384/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Gaza: Breast Cancer","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Israel following reports that it has refused to allow Palestinian women suffering from breast cancer to leave Gaza for treatment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657385","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>We are aware of the International Criminal Court's position and are following closely. It has been the position of every British Government since 1948 that the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs, i.e. the West Bank including East Jerusalem and Gaza) were not lawfully part of the state of Israel at its creation or at any point thereafter. We consider that the level of control that Israel retains over these territories amounts to occupation under international law and hence that Israel's presence in the OPTs is governed by the provisions of the Fourth Geneva Conventions of 1949, to which Israel is a state party.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:37:15.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657385/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657385/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Occupied Territories","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the International Criminal Court's affirmation of the occupied status of the Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657386","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>We recognise that Palestinians face severe difficulty in securing building permissions for homes and infrastructure in Area C. We continue to urge the government of Israel to develop improved mechanisms for zoning, planning and permitting in Area C, including by facilitating local Palestinian participation in such processes. The UK provides technical assistance to support Palestinian villages currently threatened with demolition and funding to support long-term planning for Palestinian communities in East Jerusalem and the West Bank.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:41:09.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657386/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657386/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Israel following reports that the majority of building permits applied for by Palestinians in existing Palestinian villages are rejected.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657387","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv have been in touch with the Israeli authorities to ascertain the correct procedures which need to be followed to meet Israel's customs requirements. They have been in regular contact with the Fire Brigades Union, and provided advice on the correct steps which need to be followed to proceed with the shipment.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:41:46.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657387/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657387/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","West Bank: Fire and Rescue Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Israel following reports that firefighting equipment intended for the West Bank has been detained in Haifa.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657388","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>The violence and instability in Lebanon's twelve Palestinian refugee camps remains a concern for the UK. The armed violence that took place in Ein El Hilweh on 5 December was a shocking example of the serious problems affecting daily camp life. Although it is not the UK's policy to raise specific camp security incidents with the government of Lebanon, we monitor Palestinian refugee issues closely and raise these in our regular discussions with the Lebanese Government.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:42:18.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657388/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657388/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Lebanon: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Lebanon following the condemnation by the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees of armed violence in Ein El Hilweh Palestinian refugee camp.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657389","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>An international student studying in the UK must demonstrate that they have:</p><p>• £1,265 per month for living costs if they are studying in London for the majority of their study (more than 50% of study time);</p><p>• £1,015 per month for living costs if they are studying outside London, or anywhere else in the UK, for the majority of their study (more than 50% of study time).</p><p>In most cases, an international student will need to show that they have money for their living costs for each month of their course, up to a maximum of nine months. The amount of funds that international students must demonstrate for living costs were raised in November 2015 in line with the combined maximum maintenance loan and grant available to English students living away from home starting courses in September 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4024","2017-01-09T13:11:40.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657389/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657389/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Entry Clearances: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much an international student applying for a visa to study in the UK would need to have available in order to demonstrate that they have sufficient funds to cover their living expenses if they were applying to study in (1) England, (2) Scotland, (3) Wales, and (4) Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL4023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657390","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>An international student studying in the UK must demonstrate that they have:</p><p>• £1,265 per month for living costs if they are studying in London for the majority of their study (more than 50% of study time);</p><p>• £1,015 per month for living costs if they are studying outside London, or anywhere else in the UK, for the majority of their study (more than 50% of study time).</p><p>In most cases, an international student will need to show that they have money for their living costs for each month of their course, up to a maximum of nine months. The amount of funds that international students must demonstrate for living costs were raised in November 2015 in line with the combined maximum maintenance loan and grant available to English students living away from home starting courses in September 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4023","2017-01-09T13:11:40.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657390/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657390/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Entry Clearances: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 11 November (HL2633), whether the amount that an international student applying for a visa to study in the UK would need to have available in order to demonstrate that they have sufficient funds to cover living expenses has changed since the replacement of maintenance grants with loans for UK home students.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL4024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657391","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>As of the 30 November, 5.3% of our Heads of Mission reported they were from a black or minority ethnic (BME) background (based on a 98% reporting rate).</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:42:36.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657391/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657391/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Diplomatic Service: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many resident heads of mission from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office are from a black or minority ethnic background.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL4025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657393","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>As of the 30 November, of the seven of Heads of Mission to international organisations that have reported their ethnicity (86% of the total number of Heads of Mission to international organisations), none are from a black or minority ethnic (BME) background.</p><p>Continuing to improve the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's record on diversity, equality and inclusion is fundamental to our aim of being the best diplomatic service in the world. We undertake a range of interventions to improve our leadership and management capability and to remove barriers to the progress of under-represented groups in the FCO, to help people reach their full potential. Action includes a bespoke talent development scheme for BME staff; role models from all backgrounds; diverse interview panels at all grades; diverse shortlists for senior positions as the norm; and outreach to attract diverse talent into the FCO, focused on BME candidates and those from a low-socio economic background.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:43:12.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657393/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657393/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Diplomatic Service: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many heads of mission to international organisations from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office are from a black or minority ethnic background.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL4026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657394","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-23","<p>As of the 30 November the total number of staff in the top five civil service grades and those that were from a black or minority ethnic (BME) background were:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Grade</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>Total number of staff who have reported an ethnicity</p></td><td><p>Those that reported they were BME</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>D7</p></td><td><p>430</p></td><td><p>368</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SMS1</p></td><td><p>263</p></td><td><p>230</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SMS2</p></td><td><p>102</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SMS3</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SMS4</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-23T12:43:32.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657394/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657394/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Senior Civil Servants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many staff members in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office are in the top five civil service grades; and how many of those are from a black or minority ethnic background.","false","Biography information for Baroness Berridge",,"Baroness Berridge","HL4027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657395","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","<p>The Ministry of Justice’s intention is for policy records created in 1997 and 1998 to be reviewed in 2019 for transfer to The National Archives in 2020. This is in accordance with the deadline specified by the Public Records (Transfer to the Public Record Office) (Transitional and Saving Provisions) Order 2012.</p>",,"Lord Henley","HL4077","2016-12-22T11:52:54.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657395/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657395/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-12","Human Rights Act 1998","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to authorise public access in 2017 to official records relating to the preparation of the Human Rights Bill in 1997.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657396","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>We note the issue raised and will continue to consider whether any appropriate steps need to be taken in light of any developments.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-20T16:44:30.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657396/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657396/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-12","Public Sector: Harassment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen on 6 December (HL3463), whether they will establish a cross party commission with representatives from national and local government to create an action plan to reduce the incidence of threatening behaviour against those holding public office.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL4029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657397","Department of Health","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) funds and supports research into all aspects of human health. Spend on research funded directly by NIHR is categorised by Health Research Classification System (HRCS) categories, including ‘cancer’. There are no HRCS health sub-categories, such as for pancreatic cancer.</p><p> </p><p>The NIHR invested £745 million in cancer research from 2010-11 to 2015-16 (see table below). This figure includes investment in the NIHR Liverpool Pancreatic Biomedical Research Unit, which carries out research into pancreatic cancer and other pancreatic diseases.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Cancer research</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£100,901</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£104,104</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£133,239</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£129,893</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£134,715</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£142,433</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£745,285</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Medical Research Council (MRC) spend on research into pancreatic cancer since 2011-12 is provided below. No directly comparable figure is available for 2010-11.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Pancreatic Cancer Research</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£0.37 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£1.11 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£1.66 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£2.22 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£2.66 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>To provide context, in 2015, the MRC’s overall expenditure on cancer research was £90.3 million (calendar year figure, source: National Cancer Research Institute). This figure includes a broad portfolio of site-specific and general underpinning cancer research, some of which will be relevant to research into pancreatic cancer, as it is often the case that research relevant to one site may also have implications for other forms of cancer.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-21T13:53:42.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657397/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657397/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-12","Pancreatic Cancer: Research","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the five-year survival rate for patients suffering from pancreatic cancer, what funding has been provided for research into pancreatic cancer since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL4030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657398","Department for Education","false","2016-12-20","<p>The Government is committed to raising standards of achievement in English, mathematics and science. The pupils who sat the 2015 Programme for International Student Assessment in England were born around the year 2000 and have therefore experienced only some of the changes we have introduced since 2010, and none of the changes to primary education. We have introduced rigorous new English, maths and science curricula and new qualifications to match expectations set in the highest performing jurisdictions internationally.</p><p> </p><p>For mathematics, we are providing £41m over the next four years to introduce mathematics ‘mastery’ in primary schools, based on successful teaching approaches from south-east Asia. We are funding the networks of Science Learning Partnerships and Maths Hubs to improve the quality of science and maths teaching in primary and secondary schools. We also offer significant financial incentives to attract top science and mathematics graduates into teaching and are investing up to £67m over four years to train up to an additional 2,500 maths and physics teachers and upskill 15,000 existing teachers in these subjects by the end of this parliament.</p><p>In English we have introduced a phonics check at the beginning of compulsory schooling which aims to ensure all pupils acquire the basics in literacy before the end of primary school.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-12-20T15:57:11.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657398/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657398/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-12","Schools: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the reasons for the current ranking of UK schools in the Programme for International Student Assessment survey; and whether they intend to propose measures to improve the performance of UK schools in the survey.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL4031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657399","Home Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>Prevent is about safeguarding vulnerable people from becoming terrorists or supporting terrorism. This cannot be done by Government alone, and training in Prevent plays a vital part in empowering people to safeguard those who need our help. Prevent training is kept under continued review. Those who receive training are encouraged to provide feedback on all aspects of it.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-22T15:34:56.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657399/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657399/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Counter-terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 9 December (HL3756), whether they will create a process whereby people outside the Home Office can directly feed back and challenge Prevent training when it is considered to be straying beyond a remit of safeguarding people from becoming involved in terrorism, such as by identifying anti-fracking protesters as extremists.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657400","Home Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>The enforcement of road traffic offences is an operational matter for the police, drawing on relevant statistical information as appropriate, and taking into account any specific local problems and demands.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-22T15:27:20.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657400/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657400/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Road Traffic Offences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the value to the development of enforcement policy of collating data on the number of people killed or injured resulting from drivers breaking the law.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657401","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Ministry of Justice collect statistics on the prosecution of drink drive offences and The Department for Transport collects casualty statistics involving drink driving. These statistics are published on GOV.UK The Department is working with the Ministry of Justice to see if we can make the link between drink drive prosecutions and casualties. If that is possible we intend to publish the results.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-21T11:53:11.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657401/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657401/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-12","Driving under Influence: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to collect annual figures for the prosecution of incidents of drink driving which involve a casualty.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657402","Department of Health","false","2016-12-21","<p>NHS England compiles and publishes monthly delayed transfers of care data. The data is available by each local authority and National Health Service trust, and includes the reason for the delay against a defined set of 10 categories. The data set is published in an online-only, interactive format.</p><p> </p><p>Delays have multiple causes and as a result there is variation between local authorities. A wide-ranging package of support is in place to help areas improve transfers out of hospital and reduce delays, including work as part of Accident and Emergency Improvement Plans to understand and address delays in hospital discharge and promote good practice.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS and local government have also developed new resources, including a high impact change model for reducing delayed transfers of care. In addition, the Emergency Care Improvement Programme provides tailored support to local systems to support rapid and sustained improvement in performance.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-21T13:53:02.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657402/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657402/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-12","Hospital Beds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the transfer of care rate for each local authority in England; and what assessment they have made of the reasons for any differences in the transfer of care rate between local authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL4035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657403","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-23","<p>The social care precept created in the 2015 Spending Review works by giving local authorities the flexibility to raise council tax in their area by up to 2 per cent above the existing threshold. If all local authorities used this to its maximum effect it could help raise nearly £2 billion a year by 2019-20. In 2016-17 144 out of 152 (95 per cent) adult social care authorities took up the precept raising £382 million extra for social care this year. The core spending power tables published alongside the Local Government Finance Settlement provide set out estimates of how much each council might raise in later years, and an explanatory note sets out the assumptions that these are based on.</p><p />",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-23T15:02:09.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657403/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657403/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-12","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, assuming current prices and that all English local authorities with adult social care provisions make two per cent increases in the council tax precept, how much will be raised in total for adult social care in England (1) in the first year of operation, and (2) for all years of operation up to and including the financial year 2019–20.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4036"
