"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657405","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-28","<p>Local Authorities fund adult social care services through a combination of local taxes and central grants, and make local choices about how much to spend in order to meet their duties.</p><p>The improved Better Care Fund grant, worth £1.5 Billion in 2019-20 by allocation to local authorities using a methodology which ensures every authority gets its share of the total funding available through this grant and the Social Care precept on council tax, as measured by the social care Relative Needs Formula. The Provisional Local Government Finance Settlement for 2017-18, published on 15 December, confirmed this method following a public consultation</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-28T13:15:09.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657405/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657405/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-12","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to introduce smoothing mechanisms or adjustments of grants to assist those local authorities where permitted increases in the council tax precept produce insufficient income relative to the demographic demands on their adult social care services.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657406","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-23","<p>By the end of the Parliament, local government will retain 100 per cent of taxes raised locally, giving councils control of around an additional £12.5 billion of business rates to spend on local services as they see fit, including on Adult Social Care. To ensure the reforms are fiscally neutral, new responsibilities will be devolved to local authorities. We recently conducted a consultation on our approach to the implementation of 100 per cent Business Rates Retention, which received over 450 responses. My officials are currently considering all responses and we will publish a summary of the responses and our proposals for the broad way forward in due course.</p><p>In the meantime, we will continue close collaboration with local government in taking this work forward, including through the Business Rates Retention Steering Group, which is jointly chaired by the Local Government Association (LGA) and the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG). The Steering Group was established to consider the mechanisms needed to set up and run the new business rates system, as well as the timetable and implementation of the reforms. It oversees the work of a set of technical working groups, each looking at particular aspects of the reforms. The Group meets on a regular basis and has done so on 7 occasions since April 2016. All papers for meetings are published here: <a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/business-rates" target="_blank">http://www.local.gov.uk/business-rates</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-23T14:52:31.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657406/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657406/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-12","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the transfer of business rates to local authorities will provide any scope for improving the funding of local authority adult social care services before the financial year 2020–21.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657407","Department of Health","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government remains committed to introducing a cap on care costs and extension of means-tested support, which will be implemented from April 2020.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-19T17:01:17.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657407/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657407/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-12","Social Services: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to bring into effect the provisions in the Care Act 2014 for capping individual liability for meeting the costs of adult social care; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657408","Department of Health","false","2016-12-20","<p>Care and support is arranged on an open market where prices and fee rates are negotiated locally by commissioners for state-funded clients, whilst individuals and their families do so for those who self-fund. The Government has no say in these individual negotiations.</p><p> </p><p>There are many reasons why individuals who self-fund may pay more than local authorities, including premium accommodation and services, and discounts that may be available to authorities for bulk purchasing and lower transaction costs.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Act placed duties on councils to promote their overall local market of providers to ensure it remains sustainable as to deliver high-quality services for all local people. Prices and fee rates paid by commissioners to provider organisations must reflect these new duties.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published the Care and Support statutory guidance setting out how councils should meet these new duties when commissioning, including the consideration of the actual costs of care and support when negotiating fee levels. This guidance is an online-only resource, subject to updates.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-20T12:50:05.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657408/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657408/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-12","Care Homes: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their policy regarding proprietors of nursing and residential care homes subsidising the care of publicly funded residents from payments by private payers; and what guidance they have issued on this to local authorities or care home proprietors.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL4041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657409","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>Planning policy expects that Sustainable Drainage Systems are to be provided in all major new developments (e.g. 10 dwellings or more), unless demonstrated to be inappropriate. This is in addition to existing policy that expects developments (both major or minor) in flood risk areas to give priority to the use of Sustainable Drainage Systems.</p><p>My Department, in collaboration with Defra, are currently undertaking a targeted review of national and local planning policy on Sustainable Drainage Systems to gauge the extent to which they have been successful in encouraging take-up of such drainage systems in new development.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-21T17:32:42.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657409/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657409/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-12","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to promote sustainable drainage in new house building.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657410","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-21","<p>In the last Parliament, we strengthened the energy standards for new homes by over 30 per cent. New homes built to these demanding standards are reducing bills and saving carbon.</p><p>The government has a duty under the Housing and Planning Act 2016 to carry out a review of the energy performance requirements for new homes in the Building Regulations. We have started work on this review and the outcome will be used to help determine whether any further strengthening of energy performance standards is required.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-21T17:32:58.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657410/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657410/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-12","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to promote energy efficiency in new house building.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657411","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011 requires the Non-executive members of the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) to commission an external review every five years, to examine the content and quality of the reports published by the OBR. To this end, the Page review was published in September 2014. HM Treasury published its own review of the OBR in 2015, building on evidence from the Page review.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-12-21T12:33:39.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657411/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657411/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-12","Office for Budget Responsibility","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Young of Cookham on 12 December (HL3687), whether they have made a separate assessment of the accuracy of the forecasts for the economy and public finances made by the Office for Budget Responsibility since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL4044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657412","Home Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>The UK supported the French authorities in the operation to clear the Calais camp and safely move the minors from the camp to specialist alternative accommodation across France. However the provision of care to migrants in France is the responsibility of the French Government.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-11T12:10:53.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657412/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657412/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to publish immediately a report outlining the care received in France by those under the age of 18 who are applying for admission to the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657413","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-21","<p>DFID has provided £27 million in humanitarian assistance to help tackle the refugee and migrant crisis in Greece since October 2015. This has provided life-saving assistance, according to need, to refugees and migrants from Syria and other countries. The support includes accommodation, food, water and hygiene kits.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-12-21T12:49:45.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657413/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657413/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-12","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much aid the UK has given to Greece to help accommodate and care for refugees from Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657415","Home Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>All those granted refugee status or humanitarian protection in the UK or resettled under one of our resettlement schemes are allowed to work immediately.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-22T13:46:52.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657415/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657415/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Refugees: Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether refugees from any countries are allowed to work immediately after being accepted into the UK; and, if so, from which countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657416","Home Office","false","2016-12-22","<p>Children of all nationalities who qualify for refugee status in the UK will normally be granted five years’ limited leave to remain. At the end of that five year period they will be able to apply for indefinite leave to remain if they continue to require protection.</p><p>The status of young Syrian refugees in other EU Member States is a matter for the relevant authorities in those countries.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-22T13:52:22.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657416/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657416/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-12","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what will be the status of young Syrian refugees in the EU and the UK when they reach the age of 18.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657417","The Senior Deputy Speaker","false","2016-12-19","<p>Following the decision by the Administration and Works Committee in the Lords and the Administration Committee in the Commons that in cases where encaustic tiles from the Palace of Westminster cannot be re-used elsewhere, some of these should be donated to museums or related institutions, encaustic tiles have been donated to the Tile Trail in Stoke on Trent; to a recycled mosaics project to commemorate the pottery works in Stoke on Trent; and to St Augustine’s Church in Ramsgate.</p>",,"Lord McFall of Alcluith",,"2016-12-19T14:12:45.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657417/answer","Biography information for Lord McFall of Alcluith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657417/answer",,,,,"204",,"Senior Deputy Speaker (HoL)","2016-12-12","Palace of Westminster: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask the Senior Deputy Speaker, further to the Written Answer by the Chairman of Committees on 8 April 2014, which museums or related institutions have received encaustic tiles from the Palace of Westminster.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657418","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-21","<p>The Government is undertaking a wide-ranging analysis of 50 sectors and cross-cutting regulatory issues. The Government will set out its broad plans before triggering Article 50 with the important caveat that nothing we do or say should undermine the UK’s negotiating position.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-12-21T13:48:43.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657418/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657418/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have identified each and every issue which requires separate negotiation for leaving the EU; and if so, whether they will publish a list of those issues.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL4050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657419","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-28","<p>Relationships between states should be built on honest foundations and our Government takes seriously any attempts by Foreign States to deliberately mislead. We monitor and assess these cases and respond appropriately.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-28T13:21:07.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657419/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657419/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-12","Propaganda","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the extent of misinformation by foreign states and its impact on UK relations with those states; and what action they are taking to counter this.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL4051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657824","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>Government is committed to protecting our nation's cultural heritage and does so in a number of ways. These include statutory designation of heritage assets, recognition and management of UK World Heritage Sites, export licensing systems, grant-in-aid support to sixteen museums and galleries as well as a wide range of other government and public funding.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-12-15T17:17:50.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657824/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/657824/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-12","Cultural Heritage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to protect the UK's cultural heritage.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","907916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658050","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-20","<p>DIT’s marketing campaign is targeting high potential SMEs across a number of channels and directing them to GREAT.gov.uk. We're focusing predominantly on young, small businesses with a modest turnover that have the potential to export their products and services overseas. Since going live, over 200,000 users have visited GREAT.gov.uk. More than 12,186 users have made use of our Selling Online Overseas service and 1100 businesses have created a profile on our ‘Find a Buyer’ service.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-20T17:16:13.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658050/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658050/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Small Businesses: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the level of SME business interest in the great.gov.uk digital platform.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","907898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658052","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-15","<p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, the Government is aiming to secure the best outcome for the UK as a whole. As I stated to the hon. Member in the debate on 2 November 2016, no decisions have yet been taken, but we are analysing the impacts of different scenarios in negotiations. That analysis is ongoing. We are determined to build a national consensus around our negotiating position and are listening and talking to as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible to do this. The Government wants to give UK companies the maximum freedom to trade with and operate in the Single Market – and let European businesses do the same here. The Department for Exiting the European Union, working with officials across government, continues to undertake wide-ranging data analysis looking at over 50 sectors as well as cross-cutting regulatory issues. The Department is also engaging widely with representatives from sectors. This work will inform the UK's position for the upcoming negotiations with our EU partners.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-15T16:59:14.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658052/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658052/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU customs union on levels of employment.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","907890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658053","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-15","<p>We are focussed on securing the best possible deal for the United Kingdom as we leave the European Union. Once we have left, it will be for the United Kingdom to decide how taxpayers' money is spent. We will seek the best access to and ability to trade within the single market for all UK companies.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","907892","2016-12-15T15:31:02.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658053/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658053/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether it is his policy to retain preferential access to the EU single market by continuing to make financial contributions to the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","907900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658055","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-15","<p>We are focussed on securing the best possible deal for the United Kingdom as we leave the European Union. Once we have left, it will be for the United Kingdom to decide how taxpayers' money is spent. We will seek the best access to and ability to trade within the single market for all UK companies.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","907900","2016-12-15T15:31:02.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658055/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/658055/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-12","EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether it is his policy to retain preferential access to the EU single market by continuing to make financial contributions to the EU after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","907892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659402","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-15","<p>The UK has a strong history in protecting human rights. While we remain members of the EU, we will continue to support a trade liberalising agenda and the UK will participate constructively in EU decision making on trade issues, including on human rights requirements.</p><p>The UK has long supported the promotion of our values globally and this will continue as we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-12-15T17:48:43.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659402/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659402/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-12-12","Trade Agreements: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that UK trade and investment agreements protect human rights.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","907899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659403","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>We reconginse MG Alba's contribution to Gaelic language broadcasting.</p><p>We have enshrined, <em>for the first time</em>, a new commitment for the BBC in the Framework Agreement to continue their partnership with MG Alba for the next 11 years, continuing to deliver output in Gaelic.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-12-15T13:13:07.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659403/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659403/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659403/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-12","Broadcasting: Scots Gaelic Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to support the future of Gaelic broadcasting.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","907926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659404","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p><strong>Tomorrow is this country’s first ever Local Charities Day, when we can celebrate the small, local charities that make such a difference to our communities. </strong><strong>I have written to all Parliamentarians asking them to support Local Charities Day and DCMS Ministers will be visiting local charities. </strong></p><p />","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-12-15T17:38:24.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659404/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659404/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-12","Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on supporting Local Charities Day 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","907922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659405","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>What individuals or clubs pay in tax is a matter for HM Revenues and Customs, and football clubs, players and managers are treated no different to others and expected to adhere to the same principals.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-12-15T15:37:41.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659405/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659405/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-12","Football: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions her Department has had with football authorities on tax avoidance by football clubs, managers and players.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","907921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659406","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p><strong>The Government recognises the importance of libraries to local communities. Local authorities are responsible for funding library services in England, and made net investment of £701 million in 2015/16. In addition, DCMS has established a £4 million ‘Libraries: Opportunities for Everyone’ fund, managed by the Arts Council and funded a £2.6 million programme to ensure wifi is available in nearly every public library in England</strong><strong>.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-12-15T17:39:27.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659406/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659406/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-12","Public Libraries: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to provide financial support for library provision.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","907923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659407","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Government has committed £7m of funding for organisations supporting victims and survivors of sexual abuse for the current financial year.</p><p>The majority of this money is provided directly to Police and Crime Commissioners to support local organisations.</p><p>Over half a million pounds was shared between national support organisations, including organisations like NAPAC, the National Association for People Abused in Childhood.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-12-15T15:37:01.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659407/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/659407/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-12","Football: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps the Government is taking to support people affected by allegations of sexual abuse in football.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","907925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655671","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government fully supports ratification and implementation of the Illicit Trade Protocol, and the UK played a leading role in negotiating and agreeing the text.</p><p> </p><p>It is UK policy to have all necessary implementing legislation in place before ratifying any international agreement. While many of the requirements of the Protocol are already in place in the UK, the requirement for licensing of tobacco manufacturing machinery is still outstanding. The Government published draft legislation to implement this provision on 5 December 2016 as part of the draft Finance Bill 2017. Subject to Parliamentary approval, the text of the Protocol can be laid before Parliament as a Command Paper with an Explanatory Memorandum. Providing Parliament does not resolve against ratification then the UK can begin the formal ratification process.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs has received a number of representations from MPs, MEPs and health lobbyist supporting early implementation and ratification of the Protocol. No discussions have been held with the tobacco industry on ratification, beyond those conducted as part of the recent consultation on implementation of licensing of tobacco manufacturing machinery.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","56890 ; 56891","2016-12-19T14:46:46.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655671/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655671/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-09","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what processes are required before the UK ratifies the World Health Organisation Protocol to Eliminate Illicit Trade in Tobacco Products.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","56889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655672","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Government fully supports ratification and implementation of the Illicit Trade Protocol, and the UK played a leading role in negotiating and agreeing the text.</p><p> </p><p>It is UK policy to have all necessary implementing legislation in place before ratifying any international agreement. While many of the requirements of the Protocol are already in place in the UK, the requirement for licensing of tobacco manufacturing machinery is still outstanding. The Government published draft legislation to implement this provision on 5 December 2016 as part of the draft Finance Bill 2017. Subject to Parliamentary approval, the text of the Protocol can be laid before Parliament as a Command Paper with an Explanatory Memorandum. Providing Parliament does not resolve against ratification then the UK can begin the formal ratification process.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs has received a number of representations from MPs, MEPs and health lobbyist supporting early implementation and ratification of the Protocol. No discussions have been held with the tobacco industry on ratification, beyond those conducted as part of the recent consultation on implementation of licensing of tobacco manufacturing machinery.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","56889 ; 56891","2016-12-19T14:46:46.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655672/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/655672/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-09","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent representations the Government has received on the ratification of the World Health Organisation Protocol to Eliminate Illicit Trade in Tobacco Products.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","56890"
